# Scrybe — Cursor IDE Rules

## Architecture: Python on the outside, Rust on the inside

- All core logic lives in Rust crates (`scrybe-core`, `scrybe-render`, etc.)
- Python is the *distribution wrapper* only — maturin `bindings = "bin"` packages Rust binaries as Python wheels
- scrybe-app is Tauri 2 (Rust + TypeScript/CodeMirror 6) — no React, no heavy frameworks
- Never add Python runtime logic to a crate that is `bindings = "bin"`

## Code style

### Rust
- `cargo fmt` always; never commit unformatted code
- `cargo clippy -- -D warnings`; zero warnings is the policy
- No `unwrap()` in library code; use `?` or explicit error handling
- Prefer `thiserror` for error types, `anyhow` at call sites
- Doc-comment all public items (`///`)

### TypeScript (scrybe-app)
- Strict mode enabled; no `any` without a comment
- CSS co-located in `src/styles/<feature>.css`
- No external UI frameworks — vanilla TS + CSS

### Python (scrybe-py, tooling)
- `black` formatting, `ruff` lint — zero warnings
- `mypy` type annotations on all public functions
- `pytest` — all tests pass before committing

## Testing

- Rust: `cargo test --all` — every public API has a test
- TypeScript: Tauri IPC commands tested via Rust unit tests
- Mock external resources (network, filesystem, subprocess) in all tests
- Never hit real services in unit tests

## Git

- Branch from `main`; never commit directly to `main`
- Commit messages: `type(scope): summary` (feat/fix/refactor/test/docs/ci)
- Include `Co-Authored-By:` agent line on all agent commits
- Pre-push hook runs full check suite; never `--no-verify`

## Build system

- `just check` = full lint + test suite
- `just install` = build Tauri app + Python wheels, install to ~/Applications + ~/venv/bin
- Tauri builds: always `npm run tauri build` (not plain `cargo build`) so frontend is embedded
- Install: always `rm -rf ~/Applications/Scrybe.app` then `cp -R ... ~/Applications/`

## License

AGPL-3.0-or-later. Every new source file must include the SPDX header:
```
// SPDX-License-Identifier: AGPL-3.0-or-later
```
